>
  <h2>The repairs we see most</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pipe boot failures</strong> — rubber cracks at the 7–10 year mark. $275–$450 per boot to replace properly. Cause of probably 40% of "mystery" ceiling leaks.</li>
    <li><strong>Ridge-cap lift</strong> — common after 60+ mph wind events. If only a few caps are lifted, a targeted repair is honest. If it's widespread, we'll tell you.</li>
    <li><strong>Flashing at wall step-ins</strong> — especially where a roof meets a chimney or a second-story wall. Water takes the path of least resistance, and bad step flashing is usually it.</li>
    <li><strong>Nail pops</strong> — nails backing out push through the shingle above; every one is a potential leak.</li>
    <li><strong>Granule loss + blister patches</strong> — often a sign the roof is near end-of-life; we'll show you photos and let you decide.</li>
  </ul>
  <h2>When we say "just repair it"</h2>
  <p>We're happy to repair. We won't upsell a replacement when a $650 repair will give you another five good years. The forty-photo packet we leave with you shows the rest of the roof too, so you know what to watch.</p>
  <h2>When we say "it's time to replace"</h2>
  <p>If the roof is in its replacement window (20+ years on 3-tab, 25+ on architectural, any age after a hail event with structural damage), a patch is throwing money at a lost cause. We'll show you why.</p>
